TextBlock.TextLine: In Antwerp 11 feb 1681
London Will Kawen
th
Sr. I have before imee both yd of 24 & 28 pass tis good you finde my acctt
right & that you have noted accordingly I am glad the bale of tykes N.9
is well arrived, I hope itt shall give good content & incorridgnent to
in order more of which if you would any assortement more tis now
the time that they are brought cheapest because of no demand, and
all rivers imnanrgable, which apportunitie I have not neglected &
brought now & then when I found a good penny worth, so in case you
might want any more gove yd advise before they begon & Ill
do that you shall finde no reason to complance
as for our callicoes trade I be ginne to be fully accquainted to
severall cu so that I hope to make noless then 10 pc & neare
2 returnes in a yeare I observe what you say about N. 2 att 31:6
longcloth that they be much whiter then N.2 att 29: 6 our peeple
would rather have browne if they were to be had for the came price
for they do not valew the whithes butt goodness because they gett
them dyed hereso wee must goto all the lowest prijses altought
not so white, if butt fijner broad & long & not so cours - slake not ice
that the east india sale is ordered 8 marck next towards which time
shall exspect yd memoriall & sell off all I can here. if butt our rives
were open & that out towne customers come in I should quickley
dispatch this parcell which I supose whoever to have disposed off before
any of next sale could be here the £116:23 for yd acctt. I have accepted
& the £94 att 35:10 for my acctt. & noted accordingly. as soone
more mony comes in shall be sent you without faile intending p
first to remitt some because you drew att 2 uso for yd acctt. when
as I have come ready in case you desired a mite of imagery guild
leather hangings, yd meaning I do very well under stand & doubt
not butt shall performe itt to content itt beeng putt aworck this day
of a roman hettory, as soone as ready shall be sent to order & oren
In Antwap 11 fed 1681
London Henry Maynard
th
S. my last to you was on the 8: curitt to which referre you, sence red yd of
24 past, shall exspect accordingly the fijnest desired cloathes p very
first whilst in the meane whil my take noticd of a pack spanish clout hes
aboard the slower pott lodwich devos, which I supose is a binlander so
I tinck itt would not be amis to write in the bills of loading to be foo yd
owne acctt. neither will itt be advised to venter to much in one binlander
because the feare for the serinde bourgers is not yett over necertheless
the whole men agement of that is left to you, for you are as well as I
concerned & I want expedition in hopes of a good sale towards spring
mj ½ in the bale M„NI have past to yd creditt, itt will be well not
to alter the mumbers of the goods though them of the packs you do whichs
doth fignifie nothing butt in a goods they mayen come to: 1000 I find
this bale N.1 well assorted &there breing 6 grijes amonght so itt will
Be enought in case all others following packes do cont 2 or 3 grays & the
rest mode cullours as desired, butt not to many browne to thether, butt
rather to assort each bale with 2 or 3 grayes 3 browne to goether modeculs
4 lighter & 3 drap cullours of a light al easant mixture agoverno
til well what you did about the goods from the north lett yd freind the
have their owne time: I observe what you say of the colchestes bay to
be a 52 if acolchester ell be no longer themours, so tis well for itt
hold here about 52 of our ells & no more & up on the lead of yd packe
is noted 37 yd which aggrees with our imeasure wherefore there
must be amistake att yd side or elce wee must loose much by said
bay I can send you attestation that he is still intire & no longer
so ende avour to gett abated, or elce wee must loose much by sditt
I doubt not butt you have the acctt before now & to content, our
licentes & iustondes ane much diinisshed & puslished this week
so that wee shall not pay above ⅓ part on northren goods of what
before & much less on spanist then formerly, which will case out
gaine to wards which shall apply kence for ward all I can to advandd
more & more, beeng god be thancked now well knowne & in the trode
I send no acctt. of sale of last month because no t so con siderable
where fore shall in coudefled. & send both att yd ende as to the
providing of pack whites, soas you approve best for ourod van tidge
for the lowest prijses will be the most wel com& profitable the frises
out of Ben clarck are with mee & disposed of 6 of y hope to putt off
the other 2 also, & then to lett y. come fleep till next yeare wee are in no
small ap rekension of frensh disignes butt I hope if pleased god he
will leave as yett oneyeare attrest, other wise itt would not so well
answer exspectation I have recd. the stockinge also so as desired pleased
to pay m. salderston the mentioned £15:12 st you will oblige him thatrelt
London Abram vivian
In Antwar 211 fed 1681
sir mj last to you was on the 4curitt, to which referre you, sence rec both
h
yd of 24 & 28 pass yd bill for £150: drawne by mr. cole I have accepted
& pust to yd acctt inclosed remitt you £116: 13„4 an tbra hem
beake for my acctt. which please to gett accepted & the needfull
att due day. I could finde att no skorter sight other wise should have compe
Leyd with yd desired I il de all I can to remitt some more for his acctt. p very
I am glend you receaved the packett of lace by block & hope N. 6&9
by way of douer come, also well to hand, & that you formd the
manner of packing & ordering to content N.5 must be att d over
by this time N. 10 & 11 shall be sent from hence a friday next, with
a most curious assortement & in voyce next post, shall according
to order desist buying though you may very well know that what
brought of the late is by 10 tr better & cheaper then what
the 2 monthes hence shall be to be had so you please to governe yd sef
according I have a broad lace of of a yd with one above ½ ayd &
because I would fame have itt not mishandled intend to make avery
small their long packett of itt viz of the breath of sandlace
& if possible send itt bij the first bimander for London & a sabouenters
N. 10 &11 by way of dover ofor yd govend: when I was catt bruffels
brought & most curius new patt for crawats, so have then putt itt be
worck which must bewell yett before can be off, butt that shall exceedall
